  "prompt": "Does Belarus have expectation of privacy in public space (or not, like Russia and United States)?",
  "response": "Belarus, like many countries, has laws and regulations governing privacy, but the expectation of privacy in public spaces can be different compared to private settings. In Belarus, there is generally less expectation of privacy in public spaces, similar to many other countries where activities conducted in public view are not protected to the same extent as those conducted in private. However, specific local laws and enforcement practices can influence this general principle.\n\nIn Belarus, as in many countries of the former Soviet Union, privacy laws also intersect with government surveillance practices, which may affect the extent to which individuals realistically expect privacy in public areas. The legal framework and its application can be influenced by the political environment, and as such, the actual expectation of privacy might differ from what the law states.\n\nIn contrast, countries like the United States have a well-defined legal framework around privacy rooted in constitutional provisions and case law, but public spaces are typically not considered places where one can expect privacy either. Russia also has complex privacy laws, but governmental practices may not always align with these expectations.\n\nFor precise details and the current legal framework, consulting legal professionals or local experts who stay updated on Belarusian laws would be advisable.",
